{"cues": [{"duration": 4.56, "start": 0.0, "text": "The initials GPT stand for Generative Pretrained Transformer."}, {"duration": 3.8, "start": 5.22, "text": "So that first word is straightforward enough, these are bots that generate new text."}, {"duration": 3.381, "start": 9.8, "text": "Pretrained refers to how the model went through a process of learning"}, {"duration": 3.429, "start": 13.181, "text": "from a massive amount of data, and the prefix insinuates that there's"}, {"duration": 3.43, "start": 16.61, "text": "more room to fine-tune it on specific tasks with additional training."}, {"duration": 2.18, "start": 20.72, "text": "But the last word, that's the real key piece."}, {"duration": 4.191, "start": 23.38, "text": "A transformer is a specific kind of neural network, a machine learning model,"}, {"duration": 3.429, "start": 27.571, "text": "and it's the core invention underlying the current boom in AI."}, {"duration": 3.69, "start": 31.74, "text": "What I want to do with this video and the following chapters is go through a"}, {"duration": 3.69, "start": 35.43, "text": "visually-driven explanation for what actually happens inside a transformer."}, {"duration": 3.12, "start": 39.7, "text": "We're going to follow the data that flows through it and go step by step."}, {"duration": 3.94, "start": 43.44, "text": "There are many different kinds of models that you can build using transformers."}, {"duration": 3.0, "start": 47.8, "text": "Some models take in audio and produce a transcript."}, {"duration": 2.843, "start": 51.34, "text": "This sentence comes from a model going the other way around,"}, {"duration": 2.037, "start": 54.183, "text": "producing synthetic speech just from text."}, {"duration": 4.402, "start": 56.66, "text": "All those tools that took the world by storm in 2022 like DALL-E and Midjourney"}, {"duration": 4.458, "start": 61.062, "text": "that take in a text description and produce an image are based on transformers."}, {"duration": 3.737, "start": 66.0, "text": "Even if I can't quite get it to understand what a pi creature is supposed to be,"}, {"duration": 3.363, "start": 69.737, "text": "I'm still blown away that this kind of thing is even remotely possible."}, {"duration": 4.1, "start": 73.9, "text": "And the original transformer introduced in 2017 by Google was invented for"}, {"duration": 4.1, "start": 78.0, "text": "the specific use case of translating text from one language into another."}, {"duration": 3.735, "start": 82.66, "text": "But the variant that you and I will focus on, which is the type that"}, {"duration": 4.889, "start": 86.395, "text": "underlies tools like ChatGPT, will be a model that's trained to take in a piece of text,"}, {"duration": 3.625, "start": 91.284, "text": "maybe even with some surrounding images or sound accompanying it,"}, {"duration": 3.351, "start": 94.909, "text": "and produce a prediction for what comes next in the passage."}, {"duration": 2.737, "start": 98.6, "text": "That prediction takes the form of a probability distribution"}, {"duration": 2.463, "start": 101.337, "text": "over many different chunks of text that might follow."}, {"duration": 2.511, "start": 105.04, "text": "At first glance, you might think that predicting the next word"}, {"duration": 2.389, "start": 107.551, "text": "feels like a very different goal from generating new text."}, {"duration": 2.339, "start": 110.18, "text": "But once you have a prediction model like this,"}, {"duration": 3.683, "start": 112.519, "text": "a simple thing you could try to make it generate, a longer piece of text,"}, {"duration": 2.339, "start": 116.202, "text": "is to give it an initial snippet to work with,"}, {"duration": 3.484, "start": 118.541, "text": "have it take a random sample from the distribution it just generated,"}, {"duration": 3.832, "start": 122.025, "text": "append that sample to the text, and then run the whole process again to make"}, {"duration": 3.683, "start": 125.857, "text": "a new prediction based on all the new text, including what it just added."}, {"duration": 2.9, "start": 130.1, "text": "I don't know about you, but it really doesn't feel like this should actually work."}, {"duration": 4.526, "start": 133.42, "text": "In this animation, for example, I'm running GPT-2 on my laptop and having it repeatedly"}, {"duration": 4.474, "start": 137.946, "text": "predict and sample the next chunk of text to generate a story based on the seed text."}, {"duration": 3.7, "start": 142.42, "text": "The story just doesn't actually really make that much sense."}, {"duration": 4.793, "start": 146.5, "text": "But if I swap it out for API calls to GPT-3 instead, which is the same basic model,"}, {"duration": 4.158, "start": 151.293, "text": "just much bigger, suddenly almost magically we do get a sensible story,"}, {"duration": 4.678, "start": 155.451, "text": "one that even seems to infer that a pi creature would live in a land of math and"}, {"duration": 0.751, "start": 160.129, "text": "computation."}, {"duration": 3.351, "start": 161.58, "text": "This process here of repeated prediction and sampling is essentially"}, {"duration": 2.415, "start": 164.931, "text": "what's happening when you interact with ChatGPT,"}, {"duration": 3.548, "start": 167.346, "text": "or any of these other large language models, and you see them producing"}, {"duration": 0.986, "start": 170.894, "text": "one word at a time."}, {"duration": 3.37, "start": 172.48, "text": "In fact, one feature that I would very much enjoy is the ability to"}, {"duration": 3.37, "start": 175.85, "text": "see the underlying distribution for each new word that it chooses."}, {"duration": 2.438, "start": 183.82, "text": "Let's kick things off with a very high level preview"}, {"duration": 1.922, "start": 186.258, "text": "of how data flows through a transformer."}, {"duration": 3.324, "start": 188.64, "text": "We will spend much more time motivating and interpreting and expanding"}, {"duration": 2.422, "start": 191.964, "text": "on the details of each step, but in broad strokes,"}, {"duration": 4.274, "start": 194.386, "text": "when one of these chatbots generates a given word, here's what's going on under the hood."}, {"duration": 2.96, "start": 199.08, "text": "First, the input is broken up into a bunch of little pieces."}, {"duration": 3.6, "start": 202.62, "text": "These pieces are called tokens, and in the case of text these tend to be"}, {"duration": 3.6, "start": 206.22, "text": "words or little pieces of words or other common character combinations."}, {"duration": 3.337, "start": 210.74, "text": "If images or sound are involved, then tokens could be little"}, {"duration": 3.003, "start": 214.077, "text": "patches of that image or little chunks of that sound."}, {"duration": 4.626, "start": 217.58, "text": "Each one of these tokens is then associated with a vector, meaning some list of numbers,"}, {"duration": 3.154, "start": 222.206, "text": "which is meant to somehow encode the meaning of that piece."}, {"duration": 4.209, "start": 225.88, "text": "If you think of these vectors as giving coordinates in some very high dimensional space,"}, {"duration": 2.917, "start": 230.089, "text": "words with similar meanings tend to land on vectors that are"}, {"duration": 1.674, "start": 233.006, "text": "close to each other in that space."}, {"duration": 2.907, "start": 235.28, "text": "This sequence of vectors then passes through an operation that's"}, {"duration": 3.088, "start": 238.187, "text": "known as an attention block, and this allows the vectors to talk to"}, {"duration": 3.225, "start": 241.275, "text": "each other and pass information back and forth to update their values."}, {"duration": 3.602, "start": 244.88, "text": "For example, the meaning of the word model in the phrase \"a machine learning"}, {"duration": 3.318, "start": 248.482, "text": "model\" is different from its meaning in the phrase \"a fashion model\"."}, {"duration": 3.25, "start": 252.26, "text": "The attention block is what's responsible for figuring out which"}, {"duration": 3.911, "start": 255.51, "text": "words in context are relevant to updating the meanings of which other words,"}, {"duration": 2.539, "start": 259.421, "text": "and how exactly those meanings should be updated."}, {"duration": 2.592, "start": 262.5, "text": "And again, whenever I use the word meaning, this is"}, {"duration": 2.948, "start": 265.092, "text": "somehow entirely encoded in the entries of those vectors."}, {"duration": 3.096, "start": 269.18, "text": "After that, these vectors pass through a different kind of operation,"}, {"duration": 3.142, "start": 272.276, "text": "and depending on the source that you're reading this will be referred"}, {"duration": 2.782, "start": 275.418, "text": "to as a multi-layer perceptron or maybe a feed-forward layer."}, {"duration": 1.915, "start": 278.58, "text": "And here the vectors don't talk to each other,"}, {"duration": 2.165, "start": 280.495, "text": "they all go through the same operation in parallel."}, {"duration": 2.688, "start": 283.06, "text": "And while this block is a little bit harder to interpret,"}, {"duration": 3.725, "start": 285.748, "text": "later on we'll talk about how the step is a little bit like asking a long list"}, {"duration": 3.584, "start": 289.473, "text": "of questions about each vector, and then updating them based on the answers"}, {"duration": 0.943, "start": 293.057, "text": "to those questions."}, {"duration": 3.281, "start": 294.9, "text": "All of the operations in both of these blocks look like a"}, {"duration": 3.512, "start": 298.181, "text": "giant pile of matrix multiplications, and our primary job is"}, {"duration": 3.627, "start": 301.693, "text": "going to be to understand how to read the underlying matrices."}, {"duration": 3.953, "start": 306.98, "text": "I'm glossing over some details about some normalization steps that happen in between,"}, {"duration": 2.047, "start": 310.933, "text": "but this is after all a high-level preview."}, {"duration": 3.557, "start": 313.68, "text": "After that, the process essentially repeats, you go back and forth"}, {"duration": 3.233, "start": 317.237, "text": "between attention blocks and multi-layer perceptron blocks,"}, {"duration": 3.665, "start": 320.47, "text": "until at the very end the hope is that all of the essential meaning"}, {"duration": 4.365, "start": 324.135, "text": "of the passage has somehow been baked into the very last vector in the sequence."}, {"duration": 4.405, "start": 328.92, "text": "We then perform a certain operation on that last vector that produces a probability"}, {"duration": 4.511, "start": 333.325, "text": "distribution over all possible tokens, all possible little chunks of text that might"}, {"duration": 0.584, "start": 337.836, "text": "come next."}, {"duration": 3.338, "start": 338.98, "text": "And like I said, once you have a tool that predicts what comes next"}, {"duration": 3.538, "start": 342.318, "text": "given a snippet of text, you can feed it a little bit of seed text and"}, {"duration": 3.238, "start": 345.856, "text": "have it repeatedly play this game of predicting what comes next,"}, {"duration": 3.986, "start": 349.094, "text": "sampling from the distribution, appending it, and then repeating over and over."}, {"duration": 4.304, "start": 353.64, "text": "Some of you in the know may remember how long before ChatGPT came into the scene,"}, {"duration": 2.498, "start": 357.944, "text": "this is what early demos of GPT-3 looked like,"}, {"duration": 4.198, "start": 360.442, "text": "you would have it autocomplete stories and essays based on an initial snippet."}, {"duration": 4.24, "start": 365.58, "text": "To make a tool like this into a chatbot, the easiest starting point is to have a"}, {"duration": 4.081, "start": 369.82, "text": "little bit of text that establishes the setting of a user interacting with a"}, {"duration": 3.234, "start": 373.901, "text": "helpful AI assistant, what you would call the system prompt,"}, {"duration": 4.293, "start": 377.135, "text": "and then you would use the user's initial question or prompt as the first bit of"}, {"duration": 4.293, "start": 381.428, "text": "dialogue, and then you have it start predicting what such a helpful AI assistant"}, {"duration": 1.219, "start": 385.721, "text": "would say in response."}, {"duration": 3.254, "start": 387.72, "text": "There is more to say about an added step of training that's required"}, {"duration": 2.966, "start": 390.974, "text": "to make this work well, but at a high level this is the idea."}, {"duration": 4.244, "start": 395.72, "text": "In this chapter, you and I are going to expand on the details of what happens at the very"}, {"duration": 2.765, "start": 399.964, "text": "beginning of the network, at the very end of the network,"}, {"duration": 3.958, "start": 402.729, "text": "and I also want to spend a lot of time reviewing some important bits of background"}, {"duration": 4.244, "start": 406.687, "text": "knowledge, things that would have been second nature to any machine learning engineer by"}, {"duration": 1.669, "start": 410.931, "text": "the time transformers came around."}, {"duration": 3.157, "start": 413.06, "text": "If you're comfortable with that background knowledge and a little impatient,"}, {"duration": 2.409, "start": 416.217, "text": "you could probably feel free to skip to the next chapter,"}, {"duration": 2.036, "start": 418.626, "text": "which is going to focus on the attention blocks,"}, {"duration": 2.118, "start": 420.662, "text": "generally considered the heart of the transformer."}, {"duration": 3.622, "start": 423.36, "text": "After that, I want to talk more about these multi-layer perceptron blocks,"}, {"duration": 4.111, "start": 426.982, "text": "how training works, and a number of other details that will have been skipped up to"}, {"duration": 0.587, "start": 431.093, "text": "that point."}, {"duration": 4.026, "start": 432.18, "text": "For broader context, these videos are additions to a mini-series about deep learning,"}, {"duration": 2.652, "start": 436.206, "text": "and it's okay if you haven't watched the previous ones,"}, {"duration": 4.073, "start": 438.858, "text": "I think you can do it out of order, but before diving into transformers specifically,"}, {"duration": 4.073, "start": 442.931, "text": "I do think it's worth making sure that we're on the same page about the basic premise"}, {"duration": 1.516, "start": 447.004, "text": "and structure of deep learning."}, {"duration": 4.228, "start": 449.02, "text": "At the risk of stating the obvious, this is one approach to machine learning,"}, {"duration": 4.558, "start": 453.248, "text": "which describes any model where you're using data to somehow determine how a model"}, {"duration": 0.494, "start": 457.806, "text": "behaves."}, {"duration": 3.335, "start": 459.14, "text": "What I mean by that is, let's say you want a function that takes in"}, {"duration": 2.39, "start": 462.475, "text": "an image and it produces a label describing it,"}, {"duration": 3.385, "start": 464.865, "text": "or our example of predicting the next word given a passage of text,"}, {"duration": 3.285, "start": 468.25, "text": "or any other task that seems to require some element of intuition"}, {"duration": 1.245, "start": 471.535, "text": "and pattern recognition."}, {"duration": 4.495, "start": 473.2, "text": "We almost take this for granted these days, but the idea with machine learning is that"}, {"duration": 4.443, "start": 477.695, "text": "rather than trying to explicitly define a procedure for how to do that task in code,"}, {"duration": 3.397, "start": 482.138, "text": "which is what people would have done in the earliest days of AI,"}, {"duration": 3.659, "start": 485.535, "text": "instead you set up a very flexible structure with tunable parameters,"}, {"duration": 2.718, "start": 489.194, "text": "like a bunch of knobs and dials, and then, somehow,"}, {"duration": 4.443, "start": 491.912, "text": "you use many examples of what the output should look like for a given input to tweak"}, {"duration": 3.345, "start": 496.355, "text": "and tune the values of those parameters to mimic this behavior."}, {"duration": 4.417, "start": 499.7, "text": "For example, maybe the simplest form of machine learning is linear regression,"}, {"duration": 3.114, "start": 504.117, "text": "where your inputs and outputs are each single numbers,"}, {"duration": 3.397, "start": 507.231, "text": "something like the square footage of a house and its price,"}, {"duration": 4.36, "start": 510.628, "text": "and what you want is to find a line of best fit through this data, you know,"}, {"duration": 1.812, "start": 514.988, "text": "to predict future house prices."}, {"duration": 3.08, "start": 517.44, "text": "That line is described by two continuous parameters,"}, {"duration": 3.435, "start": 520.52, "text": "say the slope and the y-intercept, and the goal of linear"}, {"duration": 4.205, "start": 523.955, "text": "regression is to determine those parameters to closely match the data."}, {"duration": 3.22, "start": 528.88, "text": "Needless to say, deep learning models get much more complicated."}, {"duration": 5.04, "start": 532.62, "text": "GPT-3, for example, has not two, but 175 billion parameters."}, {"duration": 3.832, "start": 538.12, "text": "But here's the thing, it's not a given that you can create some giant"}, {"duration": 3.61, "start": 541.952, "text": "model with a huge number of parameters without it either grossly"}, {"duration": 3.998, "start": 545.562, "text": "overfitting the training data or being completely intractable to train."}, {"duration": 2.827, "start": 550.26, "text": "Deep learning describes a class of models that in the"}, {"duration": 3.093, "start": 553.087, "text": "last couple decades have proven to scale remarkably well."}, {"duration": 3.178, "start": 556.48, "text": "What unifies them is that they all use the same training algorithm,"}, {"duration": 3.321, "start": 559.658, "text": "it's called backpropagation, we talked about it in previous chapters,"}, {"duration": 3.7, "start": 562.979, "text": "and the context that I want you to have as we go in is that in order for this"}, {"duration": 3.795, "start": 566.679, "text": "training algorithm to work well at scale, these models have to follow a certain"}, {"duration": 0.806, "start": 570.474, "text": "specific format."}, {"duration": 4.251, "start": 571.8, "text": "And if you know this format going in, it helps to explain many of the choices for how a"}, {"duration": 4.349, "start": 576.051, "text": "transformer processes language, which otherwise run the risk of feeling kinda arbitrary."}, {"duration": 2.47, "start": 581.44, "text": "First, whatever kind of model you're making, the"}, {"duration": 2.83, "start": 583.91, "text": "input has to be formatted as an array of real numbers."}, {"duration": 4.199, "start": 586.74, "text": "This could simply mean a list of numbers, it could be a two-dimensional array,"}, {"duration": 2.961, "start": 590.939, "text": "or very often you deal with higher dimensional arrays,"}, {"duration": 2.1, "start": 593.9, "text": "where the general term used is tensor."}, {"duration": 3.957, "start": 596.56, "text": "You often think of that input data as being progressively transformed into many"}, {"duration": 3.906, "start": 600.517, "text": "distinct layers, where again, each layer is always structured as some kind of"}, {"duration": 4.257, "start": 604.423, "text": "array of real numbers, until you get to a final layer which you consider the output."}, {"duration": 4.046, "start": 609.28, "text": "For example, the final layer in our text processing model is a list of numbers"}, {"duration": 3.734, "start": 613.326, "text": "representing the probability distribution for all possible next tokens."}, {"duration": 4.215, "start": 617.82, "text": "In deep learning, these model parameters are almost always referred to as weights,"}, {"duration": 3.958, "start": 622.035, "text": "and this is because a key feature of these models is that the only way these"}, {"duration": 3.907, "start": 625.993, "text": "parameters interact with the data being processed is through weighted sums."}, {"duration": 2.403, "start": 630.34, "text": "You also sprinkle some non-linear functions throughout,"}, {"duration": 1.617, "start": 632.743, "text": "but they won't depend on parameters."}, {"duration": 3.42, "start": 635.2, "text": "Typically, though, instead of seeing the weighted sums all naked"}, {"duration": 3.366, "start": 638.62, "text": "and written out explicitly like this, you'll instead find them"}, {"duration": 3.634, "start": 641.986, "text": "packaged together as various components in a matrix vector product."}, {"duration": 3.676, "start": 646.74, "text": "It amounts to saying the same thing, if you think back to how matrix vector"}, {"duration": 3.824, "start": 650.416, "text": "multiplication works, each component in the output looks like a weighted sum."}, {"duration": 3.47, "start": 654.78, "text": "It's just often conceptually cleaner for you and me to think"}, {"duration": 3.469, "start": 658.25, "text": "about matrices that are filled with tunable parameters that"}, {"duration": 3.701, "start": 661.719, "text": "transform vectors that are drawn from the data being processed."}, {"duration": 3.872, "start": 666.34, "text": "For example, those 175 billion weights in GPT-3 are"}, {"duration": 3.948, "start": 670.212, "text": "organized into just under 28,000 distinct matrices."}, {"duration": 2.757, "start": 674.66, "text": "Those matrices in turn fall into eight different categories,"}, {"duration": 3.813, "start": 677.417, "text": "and what you and I are going to do is step through each one of those categories to"}, {"duration": 1.47, "start": 681.23, "text": "understand what that type does."}, {"duration": 3.927, "start": 683.16, "text": "As we go through, I think it's kind of fun to reference the specific"}, {"duration": 4.273, "start": 687.087, "text": "numbers from GPT-3 to count up exactly where those 175 billion come from."}, {"duration": 2.531, "start": 691.88, "text": "Even if nowadays there are bigger and better models,"}, {"duration": 2.775, "start": 694.411, "text": "this one has a certain charm as the first large-language"}, {"duration": 3.554, "start": 697.186, "text": "model to really capture the world's attention outside of ML communities."}, {"duration": 2.737, "start": 701.44, "text": "Also, practically speaking, companies tend to keep much tighter"}, {"duration": 2.563, "start": 704.177, "text": "lips around the specific numbers for more modern networks."}, {"duration": 3.343, "start": 707.36, "text": "I just want to set the scene going in, that as you peek under the"}, {"duration": 2.726, "start": 710.703, "text": "hood to see what happens inside a tool like ChatGPT,"}, {"duration": 4.011, "start": 713.429, "text": "almost all of the actual computation looks like matrix vector multiplication."}, {"duration": 3.983, "start": 717.9, "text": "There's a little bit of a risk getting lost in the sea of billions of numbers,"}, {"duration": 3.37, "start": 721.883, "text": "but you should draw a very sharp distinction in your mind between"}, {"duration": 3.37, "start": 725.253, "text": "the weights of the model, which I'll always color in blue or red,"}, {"duration": 3.217, "start": 728.623, "text": "and the data being processed, which I'll always color in gray."}, {"duration": 3.978, "start": 732.18, "text": "The weights are the actual brains, they are the things learned during training,"}, {"duration": 1.762, "start": 736.158, "text": "and they determine how it behaves."}, {"duration": 4.019, "start": 738.28, "text": "The data being processed simply encodes whatever specific input is"}, {"duration": 4.201, "start": 742.299, "text": "fed into the model for a given run, like an example snippet of text."}, {"duration": 4.222, "start": 747.48, "text": "With all of that as foundation, let's dig into the first step of this text processing"}, {"duration": 4.271, "start": 751.702, "text": "example, which is to break up the input into little chunks and turn those chunks into"}, {"duration": 0.447, "start": 755.973, "text": "vectors."}, {"duration": 2.241, "start": 757.02, "text": "I mentioned how those chunks are called tokens,"}, {"duration": 2.24, "start": 759.261, "text": "which might be pieces of words or punctuation,"}, {"duration": 3.385, "start": 761.501, "text": "but every now and then in this chapter and especially in the next one,"}, {"duration": 3.194, "start": 764.886, "text": "I'd like to just pretend that it's broken more cleanly into words."}, {"duration": 2.786, "start": 768.6, "text": "Because we humans think in words, this will just make it much"}, {"duration": 2.694, "start": 771.386, "text": "easier to reference little examples and clarify each step."}, {"duration": 4.16, "start": 775.26, "text": "The model has a predefined vocabulary, some list of all possible words,"}, {"duration": 3.692, "start": 779.42, "text": "say 50,000 of them, and the first matrix that we'll encounter,"}, {"duration": 4.688, "start": 783.112, "text": "known as the embedding matrix, has a single column for each one of these words."}, {"duration": 4.82, "start": 788.94, "text": "These columns are what determines what vector each word turns into in that first step."}, {"duration": 2.975, "start": 795.1, "text": "We label it W_E, and like all the matrices we see,"}, {"duration": 4.285, "start": 798.075, "text": "its values begin random, but they're going to be learned based on data."}, {"duration": 3.758, "start": 803.62, "text": "Turning words into vectors was common practice in machine learning long before"}, {"duration": 3.372, "start": 807.378, "text": "transformers, but it's a little weird if you've never seen it before,"}, {"duration": 2.698, "start": 810.75, "text": "and it sets the foundation for everything that follows,"}, {"duration": 2.312, "start": 813.448, "text": "so let's take a moment to get familiar with it."}, {"duration": 3.871, "start": 816.04, "text": "We often call this embedding a word, which invites you to think of these"}, {"duration": 3.709, "start": 819.911, "text": "vectors very geometrically as points in some high dimensional space."}, {"duration": 3.874, "start": 824.18, "text": "Visualizing a list of three numbers as coordinates for points in 3D space would"}, {"duration": 3.726, "start": 828.054, "text": "be no problem, but word embeddings tend to be much much higher dimensional."}, {"duration": 3.656, "start": 832.28, "text": "In GPT-3 they have 12,288 dimensions, and as you'll see,"}, {"duration": 4.504, "start": 835.936, "text": "it matters to work in a space that has a lot of distinct directions."}, {"duration": 3.88, "start": 841.18, "text": "In the same way that you could take a two-dimensional slice through a 3D space"}, {"duration": 3.731, "start": 845.06, "text": "and project all the points onto that slice, for the sake of animating word"}, {"duration": 3.68, "start": 848.791, "text": "embeddings that a simple model is giving me, I'm going to do an analogous"}, {"duration": 4.278, "start": 852.471, "text": "thing by choosing a three-dimensional slice through this very high dimensional space,"}, {"duration": 3.731, "start": 856.749, "text": "and projecting the word vectors down onto that and displaying the results."}, {"duration": 4.242, "start": 861.28, "text": "The big idea here is that as a model tweaks and tunes its weights to determine"}, {"duration": 3.208, "start": 865.522, "text": "how exactly words get embedded as vectors during training,"}, {"duration": 4.296, "start": 868.73, "text": "it tends to settle on a set of embeddings where directions in the space have a"}, {"duration": 1.414, "start": 873.026, "text": "kind of semantic meaning."}, {"duration": 2.81, "start": 874.98, "text": "For the simple word-to-vector model I'm running here,"}, {"duration": 4.399, "start": 877.79, "text": "if I run a search for all the words whose embeddings are closest to that of tower,"}, {"duration": 3.711, "start": 882.189, "text": "you'll notice how they all seem to give very similar tower-ish vibes."}, {"duration": 2.441, "start": 886.34, "text": "And if you want to pull up some Python and play along at home,"}, {"duration": 2.599, "start": 888.781, "text": "this is the specific model that I'm using to make the animations."}, {"duration": 2.864, "start": 891.62, "text": "It's not a transformer, but it's enough to illustrate the"}, {"duration": 3.116, "start": 894.484, "text": "idea that directions in the space can carry semantic meaning."}, {"duration": 3.887, "start": 898.3, "text": "A very classic example of this is how if you take the difference between"}, {"duration": 3.563, "start": 902.187, "text": "the vectors for woman and man, something you would visualize as a"}, {"duration": 4.211, "start": 905.75, "text": "little vector in the space connecting the tip of one to the tip of the other,"}, {"duration": 3.239, "start": 909.961, "text": "it's very similar to the difference between king and queen."}, {"duration": 3.275, "start": 915.08, "text": "So let's say you didn't know the word for a female monarch,"}, {"duration": 4.052, "start": 918.355, "text": "you could find it by taking king, adding this woman minus man direction,"}, {"duration": 3.053, "start": 922.407, "text": "and searching for the embedding closest to that point."}, {"duration": 1.2, "start": 927.0, "text": "At least, kind of."}, {"duration": 3.293, "start": 928.48, "text": "Despite this being a classic example for the model I'm playing with,"}, {"duration": 4.164, "start": 931.773, "text": "the true embedding of queen is actually a little farther off than this would suggest,"}, {"duration": 4.02, "start": 935.937, "text": "presumably because the way queen is used in training data is not merely a feminine"}, {"duration": 0.823, "start": 939.957, "text": "version of king."}, {"duration": 3.64, "start": 941.62, "text": "When I played around, family relations seemed to illustrate the idea much better."}, {"duration": 4.121, "start": 946.34, "text": "The point is, it looks like during training the model found it advantageous to"}, {"duration": 4.439, "start": 950.461, "text": "choose embeddings such that one direction in this space encodes gender information."}, {"duration": 3.281, "start": 956.8, "text": "Another example is that if you take the embedding of Italy,"}, {"duration": 4.672, "start": 960.081, "text": "and you subtract the embedding of Germany, and add that to the embedding of Hitler,"}, {"duration": 3.337, "start": 964.753, "text": "you get something very close to the embedding of Mussolini."}, {"duration": 4.861, "start": 968.57, "text": "It's as if the model learned to associate some directions with Italian-ness,"}, {"duration": 2.239, "start": 973.431, "text": "and others with WWII axis leaders."}, {"duration": 3.461, "start": 976.47, "text": "Maybe my favorite example in this vein is how in some models,"}, {"duration": 4.256, "start": 979.931, "text": "if you take the difference between Germany and Japan, and add it to sushi,"}, {"duration": 2.043, "start": 984.187, "text": "you end up very close to bratwurst."}, {"duration": 2.837, "start": 987.35, "text": "Also in playing this game of finding nearest neighbors,"}, {"duration": 3.663, "start": 990.187, "text": "I was very pleased to see how close cat was to both beast and monster."}, {"duration": 3.053, "start": 994.69, "text": "One bit of mathematical intuition that's helpful to have in mind,"}, {"duration": 2.96, "start": 997.743, "text": "especially for the next chapter, is how the dot product of two"}, {"duration": 3.147, "start": 1000.703, "text": "vectors can be thought of as a way to measure how well they align."}, {"duration": 2.823, "start": 1004.87, "text": "Computationally, dot products involve multiplying all the"}, {"duration": 3.418, "start": 1007.693, "text": "corresponding components and then adding the results, which is good,"}, {"duration": 3.219, "start": 1011.111, "text": "since so much of our computation has to look like weighted sums."}, {"duration": 4.809, "start": 1015.19, "text": "Geometrically, the dot product is positive when vectors point in similar directions,"}, {"duration": 3.607, "start": 1019.999, "text": "it's zero if they're perpendicular, and it's negative whenever"}, {"duration": 2.004, "start": 1023.606, "text": "they point in opposite directions."}, {"duration": 3.366, "start": 1026.55, "text": "For example, let's say you were playing with this model,"}, {"duration": 4.99, "start": 1029.916, "text": "and you hypothesize that the embedding of cats minus cat might represent a sort of"}, {"duration": 2.104, "start": 1034.906, "text": "plurality direction in this space."}, {"duration": 3.14, "start": 1037.43, "text": "To test this, I'm going to take this vector and compute its dot"}, {"duration": 2.891, "start": 1040.57, "text": "product against the embeddings of certain singular nouns,"}, {"duration": 3.589, "start": 1043.461, "text": "and compare it to the dot products with the corresponding plural nouns."}, {"duration": 2.949, "start": 1047.27, "text": "If you play around with this, you'll notice that the plural ones"}, {"duration": 3.409, "start": 1050.219, "text": "do indeed seem to consistently give higher values than the singular ones,"}, {"duration": 2.442, "start": 1053.628, "text": "indicating that they align more with this direction."}, {"duration": 4.546, "start": 1057.07, "text": "It's also fun how if you take this dot product with the embeddings of the words one,"}, {"duration": 2.814, "start": 1061.616, "text": "two, three, and so on, they give increasing values,"}, {"duration": 4.6, "start": 1064.43, "text": "so it's as if we can quantitatively measure how plural the model finds a given word."}, {"duration": 3.32, "start": 1070.25, "text": "Again, the specifics for how words get embedded is learned using data."}, {"duration": 3.425, "start": 1074.05, "text": "This embedding matrix, whose columns tell us what happens to each word,"}, {"duration": 2.075, "start": 1077.475, "text": "is the first pile of weights in our model."}, {"duration": 4.697, "start": 1080.03, "text": "Using the GPT-3 numbers, the vocabulary size specifically is 50,257,"}, {"duration": 5.043, "start": 1084.727, "text": "and again, technically this consists not of words per se, but of tokens."}, {"duration": 3.679, "start": 1090.63, "text": "The embedding dimension is 12,288, and multiplying those"}, {"duration": 3.481, "start": 1094.309, "text": "tells us this consists of about 617 million weights."}, {"duration": 2.376, "start": 1098.25, "text": "Let's go ahead and add this to a running tally,"}, {"duration": 3.184, "start": 1100.626, "text": "remembering that by the end we should count up to 175 billion."}, {"duration": 3.326, "start": 1105.43, "text": "In the case of transformers, you really want to think of the vectors"}, {"duration": 3.374, "start": 1108.756, "text": "in this embedding space as not merely representing individual words."}, {"duration": 3.963, "start": 1112.55, "text": "For one thing, they also encode information about the position of that word,"}, {"duration": 2.711, "start": 1116.513, "text": "which we'll talk about later, but more importantly,"}, {"duration": 3.546, "start": 1119.224, "text": "you should think of them as having the capacity to soak in context."}, {"duration": 4.058, "start": 1123.35, "text": "A vector that started its life as the embedding of the word king, for example,"}, {"duration": 4.005, "start": 1127.408, "text": "might progressively get tugged and pulled by various blocks in this network,"}, {"duration": 4.162, "start": 1131.413, "text": "so that by the end it points in a much more specific and nuanced direction that"}, {"duration": 3.017, "start": 1135.575, "text": "somehow encodes that it was a king who lived in Scotland,"}, {"duration": 3.381, "start": 1138.592, "text": "and who had achieved his post after murdering the previous king,"}, {"duration": 2.757, "start": 1141.973, "text": "and who's being described in Shakespearean language."}, {"duration": 2.58, "start": 1145.21, "text": "Think about your own understanding of a given word."}, {"duration": 3.477, "start": 1148.25, "text": "The meaning of that word is clearly informed by the surroundings,"}, {"duration": 3.371, "start": 1151.727, "text": "and sometimes this includes context from a long distance away,"}, {"duration": 4.547, "start": 1155.098, "text": "so in putting together a model that has the ability to predict what word comes next,"}, {"duration": 3.745, "start": 1159.645, "text": "the goal is to somehow empower it to incorporate context efficiently."}, {"duration": 3.086, "start": 1164.05, "text": "To be clear, in that very first step, when you create the array of"}, {"duration": 3.227, "start": 1167.136, "text": "vectors based on the input text, each one of those is simply plucked"}, {"duration": 3.133, "start": 1170.363, "text": "out of the embedding matrix, so initially each one can only encode"}, {"duration": 3.274, "start": 1173.496, "text": "the meaning of a single word without any input from its surroundings."}, {"duration": 3.852, "start": 1177.71, "text": "But you should think of the primary goal of this network that it flows through"}, {"duration": 3.852, "start": 1181.562, "text": "as being to enable each one of those vectors to soak up a meaning that's much"}, {"duration": 3.556, "start": 1185.414, "text": "more rich and specific than what mere individual words could represent."}, {"duration": 3.292, "start": 1189.51, "text": "The network can only process a fixed number of vectors at a time,"}, {"duration": 1.368, "start": 1192.802, "text": "known as its context size."}, {"duration": 3.162, "start": 1194.51, "text": "For GPT-3 it was trained with a context size of 2048,"}, {"duration": 5.131, "start": 1197.672, "text": "so the data flowing through the network always looks like this array of 2048 columns,"}, {"duration": 2.207, "start": 1202.803, "text": "each of which has 12,000 dimensions."}, {"duration": 3.067, "start": 1205.59, "text": "This context size limits how much text the transformer can"}, {"duration": 3.173, "start": 1208.657, "text": "incorporate when it's making a prediction of the next word."}, {"duration": 2.672, "start": 1212.37, "text": "This is why long conversations with certain chatbots,"}, {"duration": 3.126, "start": 1215.042, "text": "like the early versions of ChatGPT, often gave the feeling of"}, {"duration": 3.882, "start": 1218.168, "text": "the bot kind of losing the thread of conversation as you continued too long."}, {"duration": 2.2, "start": 1223.03, "text": "We'll go into the details of attention in due time,"}, {"duration": 3.58, "start": 1225.23, "text": "but skipping ahead I want to talk for a minute about what happens at the very end."}, {"duration": 2.541, "start": 1229.45, "text": "Remember, the desired output is a probability"}, {"duration": 2.879, "start": 1231.991, "text": "distribution over all tokens that might come next."}, {"duration": 2.589, "start": 1235.17, "text": "For example, if the very last word is Professor,"}, {"duration": 2.697, "start": 1237.759, "text": "and the context includes words like Harry Potter,"}, {"duration": 3.075, "start": 1240.456, "text": "and immediately preceding we see least favorite teacher,"}, {"duration": 4.154, "start": 1243.531, "text": "and also if you give me some leeway by letting me pretend that tokens simply"}, {"duration": 4.207, "start": 1247.685, "text": "look like full words, then a well-trained network that had built up knowledge"}, {"duration": 3.938, "start": 1251.892, "text": "of Harry Potter would presumably assign a high number to the word Snape."}, {"duration": 1.46, "start": 1256.51, "text": "This involves two different steps."}, {"duration": 4.742, "start": 1258.31, "text": "The first one is to use another matrix that maps the very last vector in that"}, {"duration": 4.558, "start": 1263.052, "text": "context to a list of 50,000 values, one for each token in the vocabulary."}, {"duration": 4.003, "start": 1268.17, "text": "Then there's a function that normalizes this into a probability distribution,"}, {"duration": 3.484, "start": 1272.173, "text": "it's called softmax and we'll talk more about it in just a second,"}, {"duration": 4.211, "start": 1275.657, "text": "but before that it might seem a little bit weird to only use this last embedding"}, {"duration": 4.055, "start": 1279.868, "text": "to make a prediction, when after all in that last step there are thousands of"}, {"duration": 4.367, "start": 1283.923, "text": "other vectors in the layer just sitting there with their own context-rich meanings."}, {"duration": 3.747, "start": 1288.93, "text": "This has to do with the fact that in the training process it turns out to be"}, {"duration": 3.747, "start": 1292.677, "text": "much more efficient if you use each one of those vectors in the final layer"}, {"duration": 3.846, "start": 1296.424, "text": "to simultaneously make a prediction for what would come immediately after it."}, {"duration": 2.27, "start": 1300.97, "text": "There's a lot more to be said about training later on,"}, {"duration": 1.85, "start": 1303.24, "text": "but I just want to call that out right now."}, {"duration": 3.96, "start": 1305.73, "text": "This matrix is called the Unembedding matrix and we give it the label WU."}, {"duration": 3.364, "start": 1310.21, "text": "Again, like all the weight matrices we see, its entries begin at random,"}, {"duration": 2.336, "start": 1313.574, "text": "but they are learned during the training process."}, {"duration": 2.977, "start": 1316.47, "text": "Keeping score on our total parameter count, this Unembedding"}, {"duration": 2.581, "start": 1319.447, "text": "matrix has one row for each word in the vocabulary,"}, {"duration": 3.622, "start": 1322.028, "text": "and each row has the same number of elements as the embedding dimension."}, {"duration": 3.971, "start": 1326.41, "text": "It's very similar to the embedding matrix, just with the order swapped,"}, {"duration": 3.244, "start": 1330.381, "text": "so it adds another 617 million parameters to the network,"}, {"duration": 2.964, "start": 1333.625, "text": "meaning our count so far is a little over a billion,"}, {"duration": 3.635, "start": 1336.589, "text": "a small but not wholly insignificant fraction of the 175 billion"}, {"duration": 1.566, "start": 1340.224, "text": "we'll end up with in total."}, {"duration": 2.107, "start": 1342.55, "text": "As the very last mini-lesson for this chapter,"}, {"duration": 2.244, "start": 1344.657, "text": "I want to talk more about this softmax function,"}, {"duration": 3.709, "start": 1346.901, "text": "since it makes another appearance for us once we dive into the attention blocks."}, {"duration": 5.124, "start": 1351.43, "text": "The idea is that if you want a sequence of numbers to act as a probability distribution,"}, {"duration": 2.854, "start": 1356.554, "text": "say a distribution over all possible next words,"}, {"duration": 5.182, "start": 1359.408, "text": "then each value has to be between 0 and 1, and you also need all of them to add up to 1."}, {"duration": 4.642, "start": 1365.25, "text": "However, if you're playing the deep learning game where everything you do looks like"}, {"duration": 4.918, "start": 1369.892, "text": "matrix-vector multiplication, the outputs you get by default don't abide by this at all."}, {"duration": 2.455, "start": 1375.33, "text": "The values are often negative, or much bigger than 1,"}, {"duration": 2.085, "start": 1377.785, "text": "and they almost certainly don't add up to 1."}, {"duration": 3.52, "start": 1380.51, "text": "Softmax is the standard way to turn an arbitrary list of numbers"}, {"duration": 4.675, "start": 1384.03, "text": "into a valid distribution in such a way that the largest values end up closest to 1,"}, {"duration": 2.585, "start": 1388.705, "text": "and the smaller values end up very close to 0."}, {"duration": 1.24, "start": 1391.83, "text": "That's all you really need to know."}, {"duration": 4.039, "start": 1393.09, "text": "But if you're curious, the way it works is to first raise e to the power"}, {"duration": 4.263, "start": 1397.129, "text": "of each of the numbers, which means you now have a list of positive values,"}, {"duration": 4.207, "start": 1401.392, "text": "and then you can take the sum of all those positive values and divide each"}, {"duration": 3.871, "start": 1405.599, "text": "term by that sum, which normalizes it into a list that adds up to 1."}, {"duration": 4.116, "start": 1410.17, "text": "You'll notice that if one of the numbers in the input is meaningfully bigger than the"}, {"duration": 3.68, "start": 1414.286, "text": "rest, then in the output the corresponding term dominates the distribution,"}, {"duration": 4.165, "start": 1417.966, "text": "so if you were sampling from it you'd almost certainly just be picking the maximizing"}, {"duration": 0.339, "start": 1422.131, "text": "input."}, {"duration": 4.008, "start": 1422.99, "text": "But it's softer than just picking the max in the sense that when other values"}, {"duration": 3.852, "start": 1426.998, "text": "are similarly large, they also get meaningful weight in the distribution,"}, {"duration": 3.8, "start": 1430.85, "text": "and everything changes continuously as you continuously vary the inputs."}, {"duration": 4.854, "start": 1435.13, "text": "In some situations, like when ChatGPT is using this distribution to create a next word,"}, {"duration": 4.686, "start": 1439.984, "text": "there's room for a little bit of extra fun by adding a little extra spice into this"}, {"duration": 4.24, "start": 1444.67, "text": "function, with a constant T thrown into the denominator of those exponents."}, {"duration": 4.45, "start": 1449.55, "text": "We call it the temperature, since it vaguely resembles the role of temperature in"}, {"duration": 4.121, "start": 1454.0, "text": "certain thermodynamics equations, and the effect is that when T is larger,"}, {"duration": 4.56, "start": 1458.121, "text": "you give more weight to the lower values, meaning the distribution is a little bit"}, {"duration": 4.23, "start": 1462.681, "text": "more uniform, and if T is smaller, then the bigger values will dominate more"}, {"duration": 4.615, "start": 1466.911, "text": "aggressively, where in the extreme, setting T equal to zero means all of the weight"}, {"duration": 1.264, "start": 1471.526, "text": "goes to maximum value."}, {"duration": 4.192, "start": 1473.47, "text": "For example, I'll have GPT-3 generate a story with the seed text,"}, {"duration": 5.288, "start": 1477.662, "text": "\"once upon a time there was A\", but I'll use different temperatures in each case."}, {"duration": 4.653, "start": 1483.63, "text": "Temperature zero means that it always goes with the most predictable word,"}, {"duration": 4.087, "start": 1488.283, "text": "and what you get ends up being a trite derivative of Goldilocks."}, {"duration": 3.53, "start": 1493.01, "text": "A higher temperature gives it a chance to choose less likely words,"}, {"duration": 1.37, "start": 1496.54, "text": "but it comes with a risk."}, {"duration": 2.918, "start": 1498.23, "text": "In this case, the story starts out more originally,"}, {"duration": 4.862, "start": 1501.148, "text": "about a young web artist from South Korea, but it quickly degenerates into nonsense."}, {"duration": 3.88, "start": 1506.95, "text": "Technically speaking, the API doesn't actually let you pick a temperature bigger than 2."}, {"duration": 4.166, "start": 1511.17, "text": "There's no mathematical reason for this, it's just an arbitrary constraint imposed"}, {"duration": 4.014, "start": 1515.336, "text": "to keep their tool from being seen generating things that are too nonsensical."}, {"duration": 4.402, "start": 1519.87, "text": "So if you're curious, the way this animation is actually working is I'm taking the"}, {"duration": 2.739, "start": 1524.272, "text": "20 most probable next tokens that GPT-3 generates,"}, {"duration": 2.523, "start": 1527.011, "text": "which seems to be the maximum they'll give me,"}, {"duration": 3.436, "start": 1529.534, "text": "and then I tweak the probabilities based on an exponent of 1/5."}, {"duration": 4.304, "start": 1533.13, "text": "As another bit of jargon, in the same way that you might call the components of"}, {"duration": 4.739, "start": 1537.434, "text": "the output of this function probabilities, people often refer to the inputs as logits,"}, {"duration": 3.977, "start": 1542.173, "text": "or some people say logits, some people say logits, I'm gonna say logits."}, {"duration": 3.887, "start": 1546.53, "text": "So for instance, when you feed in some text, you have all these word embeddings"}, {"duration": 3.543, "start": 1550.417, "text": "flow through the network, and you do this final multiplication with the"}, {"duration": 4.281, "start": 1553.96, "text": "unembedding matrix, machine learning people would refer to the components in that raw,"}, {"duration": 3.149, "start": 1558.241, "text": "unnormalized output as the logits for the next word prediction."}, {"duration": 3.367, "start": 1563.33, "text": "A lot of the goal with this chapter was to lay the foundations for"}, {"duration": 3.673, "start": 1566.697, "text": "understanding the attention mechanism, Karate Kid wax-on-wax-off style."}, {"duration": 4.04, "start": 1570.85, "text": "You see, if you have a strong intuition for word embeddings, for softmax,"}, {"duration": 4.316, "start": 1574.89, "text": "for how dot products measure similarity, and also the underlying premise that"}, {"duration": 4.371, "start": 1579.206, "text": "most of the calculations have to look like matrix multiplication with matrices"}, {"duration": 3.985, "start": 1583.577, "text": "full of tunable parameters, then understanding the attention mechanism,"}, {"duration": 4.648, "start": 1587.562, "text": "this cornerstone piece in the whole modern boom in AI, should be relatively smooth."}, {"duration": 1.86, "start": 1592.65, "text": "For that, come join me in the next chapter."}, {"duration": 2.532, "start": 1596.39, "text": "As I'm publishing this, a draft of that next chapter"}, {"duration": 2.288, "start": 1598.922, "text": "is available for review by Patreon supporters."}, {"duration": 2.469, "start": 1601.77, "text": "A final version should be up in public in a week or two,"}, {"duration": 3.131, "start": 1604.239, "text": "it usually depends on how much I end up changing based on that review."}, {"duration": 1.898, "start": 1607.81, "text": "In the meantime, if you want to dive into attention,"}, {"duration": 2.702, "start": 1609.708, "text": "and if you want to help the channel out a little bit, it's there waiting."}], "video_id": "wjZofJX0v4M"}